00:01:35.770 --> 00:01:36.300
and have been giving us feedback.

00:01:36.300 --> 00:01:39.430
We've got developers here
who are developing products

00:01:39.430 --> 00:01:41.270
to work in that environment.

00:01:41.320 --> 00:01:46.150
So we'll be discussing where we are,
where we are today,

00:01:46.150 --> 00:01:51.300
where we've come from,
and what it is you guys need to do

00:01:51.300 --> 00:01:56.300
and to learn to provide solutions
and to customize your environment

00:01:56.300 --> 00:01:59.370
to work better in this environment.

00:02:01.500 --> 00:02:05.830
So we're going to be talking
about a managed environment.

00:02:05.930 --> 00:02:09.530
So I'd like to turn the
Wayback Machine back,

00:02:09.650 --> 00:02:15.090
take us back in history five years,
back before there was a Mac OS X.

00:02:15.700 --> 00:02:21.700
And what we had then was the Mac OS,
Mac OS 9, Mac OS 8.

00:02:21.750 --> 00:02:26.650
And that was an unmanaged computer.

00:02:26.900 --> 00:02:29.740
You plugged it in.

00:02:29.760 --> 00:02:33.140
You booted, you came up to the finder,
you could do whatever you

00:02:33.230 --> 00:02:34.980
want whenever you wanted.

00:02:34.980 --> 00:02:36.940
You got up and walked
away from your machine,

00:02:36.940 --> 00:02:40.230
somebody could sit down behind you,
do whatever they want,

00:02:40.260 --> 00:02:42.560
whenever they wanted.

00:02:42.560 --> 00:02:44.940
You had no way of controlling
that environment at all.

00:02:44.940 --> 00:02:47.900
To do that,
to do any sort of control at all,

00:02:47.900 --> 00:02:50.480
you had to get additional software.

00:02:50.530 --> 00:02:54.560
Apple provided you additional software,
it was called Macintosh Manager.

00:02:54.560 --> 00:02:57.840
Macintosh Manager gave you
the notions of having multiple

00:02:57.840 --> 00:03:00.710
users use a particular machine,
putting access control,

00:03:00.710 --> 00:03:03.800
which applications could they access,
which printers could they use,

00:03:03.800 --> 00:03:05.240
a variety of things.

00:03:05.240 --> 00:03:07.990
You needed a server
to be able to do that.

00:03:08.300 --> 00:03:13.300
But you started getting the
notion of managing the computer.

00:03:13.470 --> 00:03:18.140
Well, Mac OS X comes along--let's
fast forward to the present--Mac

00:03:18.140 --> 00:03:23.450
OS X comes along and out of the box,
it's a managed environment.

00:03:23.680 --> 00:03:32.490
If I go home today and open up a
brand new computer and boot it up,

00:03:32.490 --> 00:03:32.490
turn on MacBuddy,

00:03:32.750 --> 00:03:36.300
Install the software,
pick my admin account,

00:03:36.470 --> 00:03:38.290
get up and running.

00:03:38.650 --> 00:03:42.110
I auto-login, turn on fast login,
so I just come up,

00:03:42.200 --> 00:03:44.740
I never see a login screen.

00:03:44.740 --> 00:03:49.730
The user thinks that they're not managed,
but they are.

00:03:49.910 --> 00:03:54.190
There are some things that I cannot
do as that administration user,

00:03:54.200 --> 00:03:56.500
that only a super user can do.

00:03:56.610 --> 00:03:59.920
So right out of the box,
there are at least two

00:03:59.920 --> 00:04:01.700
users of the system.

00:04:02.610 --> 00:04:07.740
and I am not, by default, the super user.

00:04:08.010 --> 00:04:11.500
So, just right out of the box,
we've got a managed environment.

00:04:11.500 --> 00:04:13.440
We put people into a home directory.

00:04:13.450 --> 00:04:16.830
They get a home directory for free,
even on a local machine.

00:04:16.900 --> 00:04:21.060
So even without any
Apple desktop management at all,

00:04:21.060 --> 00:04:22.610
you are managed.

00:04:23.250 --> 00:04:26.400
Taking that one step further,
then I start adding users.

00:04:26.480 --> 00:04:28.510
Again, if we're just even in
a local environment.

00:04:28.610 --> 00:04:31.720
So at home,
I have user accounts for my wife,

00:04:31.750 --> 00:04:33.200
for my children.

00:04:33.200 --> 00:04:34.930
I don't have any server involved.

00:04:35.120 --> 00:04:37.960
None of them--I have
no managed preferences,

00:04:38.030 --> 00:04:39.840
which is what our group primarily does.

00:04:40.050 --> 00:04:41.670
I've never run a work group manager.

00:04:41.800 --> 00:04:43.600
I still have a managed environment.

00:04:43.730 --> 00:04:48.960
I don't have access to the
data in my kids' home directory

00:04:49.600 --> 00:04:50.070
unless I go in as a super user.

00:04:50.750 --> 00:04:55.710
So we'll be discussing a little
bit of that as we just have.

00:04:56.150 --> 00:04:58.830
We're also going to be discussing
some of the customer usage

00:04:58.830 --> 00:05:00.970
scenarios that we've seen.

00:05:00.980 --> 00:05:05.360
What I just discussed briefly was just
a normal setup where I have a single

00:05:05.360 --> 00:05:08.240
machine with just multiple user accounts.

00:05:08.240 --> 00:05:10.540
That's a managed environment.

00:05:10.540 --> 00:05:13.270
We'll be talking about what Apple's
desktop management solution is,

00:05:13.270 --> 00:05:15.100
what it is, what it isn't.

00:05:15.100 --> 00:05:19.700
I'll be talking briefly a little
bit about what we've learned.

00:05:19.700 --> 00:05:21.860
So it's been a year.

00:05:21.860 --> 00:05:25.360
People are starting to--if you
went to Michael Lopp's session

00:05:25.360 --> 00:05:31.710
yesterday on the desktop solutions,
he talked about deployment, access,

00:05:31.710 --> 00:05:36.320
and assessing the deployment,
and rolling out.

00:05:36.750 --> 00:05:40.920
Well, people have been rolling
out--starting to roll out solutions.

00:05:40.920 --> 00:05:46.210
And for those of you--how many here
work in an IT department or work in IT?

00:05:46.480 --> 00:05:49.400
How many of you are
application developers?

