00:06:30.580 --> 00:06:34.200
And what it is you--70% of the people
in here--what it is you're going to

00:06:34.200 --> 00:06:36.160
need to do to work in that environment.

00:06:36.430 --> 00:06:37.320
Things you're going to need to do.

00:06:37.400 --> 00:06:39.400
Things you're going to
need to pay attention to.

00:06:39.410 --> 00:06:42.400
And really what you're going
to need to do going forward.

00:06:45.450 --> 00:06:47.830
So let's jump over to
our customer usage model,

00:06:47.830 --> 00:06:50.710
because this is the way we
think about--what we think about

00:06:50.730 --> 00:06:53.900
when we're developing software,
at least in my organization.

00:06:54.070 --> 00:06:57.980
We try and identify who
our critical customers are.

00:06:58.250 --> 00:06:59.400
Some of you are in this room.

00:06:59.400 --> 00:07:03.520
If you're not on this screen, you know,
come talk to me after the session,

00:07:03.560 --> 00:07:07.400
and we'll start paying attention
to what your usage scenario is.

00:07:07.400 --> 00:07:10.220
But what we do is we look at
various customer scenarios,

00:07:10.220 --> 00:07:13.880
and we try and gear our software and
the solution that we're developing to

00:07:13.880 --> 00:07:15.930
meet one of these customer scenarios.

00:07:16.010 --> 00:07:18.800
So the first one we have
is a one-to-one deployment.

00:07:18.800 --> 00:07:20.910
And what do I mean by that?

00:07:22.040 --> 00:07:28.490
That's a scenario whereby
I hand you a PowerBook.

00:07:29.500 --> 00:07:32.200
I own the PowerBook.

00:07:32.200 --> 00:07:33.580
You don't own the PowerBook.

00:07:33.600 --> 00:07:35.740
I have given you an
account on that PowerBook.

00:07:35.740 --> 00:07:39.300
Let's say it's employee.

00:07:39.300 --> 00:07:42.980
You do not have super user
access to that machine.

00:07:42.980 --> 00:07:44.880
You don't even have admin
access to that machine.

00:07:44.880 --> 00:07:47.510
I put everything on that machine
that you could possibly want

00:07:47.770 --> 00:07:50.510
to use that I can think of.

00:07:50.700 --> 00:07:52.320
But can you add new software to it?

00:07:52.450 --> 00:07:55.800
Not if it requires
admin access to do that.

00:07:56.110 --> 00:07:58.570
You would have to give it back to
me to install new software on it.

00:07:58.760 --> 00:08:01.180
But it's my physical machine.

00:08:01.280 --> 00:08:02.530
I give it to you.

00:08:02.740 --> 00:08:04.500
You can add bookmarks.

00:08:04.500 --> 00:08:07.000
You can do whatever you can do as a user.

00:08:07.170 --> 00:08:11.000
You have physical access to the machine,
but you don't have admin access.

00:08:11.150 --> 00:08:14.940
And one of our significant
customers of this is the schools,

00:08:14.940 --> 00:08:19.990
where schools will hand out CPUs on a
temporary or even a long-term basis.

00:08:19.990 --> 00:08:22.620
It's owned by the school system.

00:08:22.700 --> 00:08:41.400
[Transcript missing]

00:08:41.770 --> 00:08:51.320
There's a full-blown IT deployment
where I've got a server in the back,

00:08:51.320 --> 00:08:54.150
I may have Big Iron behind
the server in the back room,

00:08:54.280 --> 00:08:57.800
you've got network accounts,
I have site license software

00:08:57.880 --> 00:09:02.460
that I have in numbers of seats
that each individual can use.

00:09:02.460 --> 00:09:04.930
So I control which printers
you can have access to,

00:09:04.930 --> 00:09:08.510
which applications you
can have access to.

00:09:08.660 --> 00:09:11.290
How much data storage
you have on my servers,

00:09:11.290 --> 00:09:14.410
what servers you have access to,
what your username is,

00:09:14.410 --> 00:09:16.640
what your password is,
how often you have to

00:09:16.640 --> 00:09:20.350
change your password,
how long your password needs to be,

00:09:20.350 --> 00:09:24.340
what sites you can access,
what you can't access.

00:09:25.420 --> 00:09:30.960
I control all that you see and hear.

00:09:30.960 --> 00:09:35.640
In that particular case,
mostly the people have network accounts.

00:09:35.640 --> 00:09:39.040
So that's really useful,
but that in and of itself--and

00:09:39.040 --> 00:09:43.760
we've tried to solve some of
this--can create problems.

00:09:43.760 --> 00:09:46.990
Usually not for a big IT place,
but I was in a session yesterday

00:09:47.090 --> 00:09:51.650
where we were talking about
where a user got up and spoke at

00:09:51.700 --> 00:09:55.060
the podium--at the microphone.

00:09:55.060 --> 00:09:57.960
And he was saying,
"We still have 10BaseT.

00:09:57.960 --> 00:10:00.920
We're still deployed on
top of 10BaseT." Well,

00:10:00.920 --> 00:10:05.400
so if I have all my network storage
and it's all happening over 10BaseT,

00:10:05.400 --> 00:10:09.860
now with significant amounts of
data flowing around and lots of

00:10:09.860 --> 00:10:15.380
people using my 10BaseT network,
even just doing browsing.

00:10:15.570 --> 00:10:22.380
Downloading some of that stuff
off of the net is something

00:10:22.380 --> 00:10:24.500
we've attempted to try and solve.

00:10:24.500 --> 00:10:27.700
The other thing is the scenario
that I alluded to in the beginning,

00:10:27.700 --> 00:10:30.500
where you have an
at-home kind of setting.

00:10:30.500 --> 00:10:34.820
Though I know that some of you out
there are deploying capabilities

00:10:34.950 --> 00:10:39.660
as an IT solution as well,
this is primarily geared towards a

00:10:39.660 --> 00:10:43.500
small or very small number usage,
and that's the capabilities.

00:10:43.500 --> 00:10:47.890
However, the capabilities scenario,
which allows you to control

00:10:47.890 --> 00:10:51.480
media--so Johnny can burn a CD,
Johnny can't burn a CD,

00:10:51.500 --> 00:10:57.500
but I can--and what
applications Johnny can use.

00:10:57.500 --> 00:11:00.500
I don't want Johnny using the terminal,
those kinds of things.

00:11:00.650 --> 00:11:05.270
It's primarily for application access
control and media access control,

00:11:05.300 --> 00:11:10.890
and it's in a small environment,
but the mechanism for doing

00:11:10.890 --> 00:11:16.030
that is the same mechanism as
what is used in a big system.

00:11:16.540 --> 00:11:19.680
We don't have a separate
means for funneling that kind

00:11:19.680 --> 00:11:21.500
of data down to the system.

00:11:21.500 --> 00:11:25.080
We use the same mechanism for
capabilities as we do for a

00:11:25.130 --> 00:11:27.400
full managed environment in IT.

00:11:27.500 --> 00:11:31.820
Then we get the mobile user,
and the mobile user is a little

00:11:31.820 --> 00:11:34.490
bit different from the one-to-one
deployment I was talking about.

00:11:34.500 --> 00:11:39.780
In this case, I give you the computer,
and you have a network account.

00:11:40.070 --> 00:11:41.340
You have this computer.

00:11:41.340 --> 00:11:43.100
You sit down,
you connect up to the network,

00:11:43.260 --> 00:11:44.490
and you log in.

00:11:44.740 --> 00:11:48.050
You log in with a username and password,
and then you unplug

00:11:48.050 --> 00:11:50.310
that from the network,
and you take it home.

00:11:50.320 --> 00:11:52.950
You take it on the road with you.

00:11:54.500 --> 00:11:59.470
I have some medium of control,
but maybe not as much.

00:11:59.580 --> 00:12:04.400
I may say that you can
access the CD or not.

00:12:04.600 --> 00:12:07.400
But it's in a mixed kind of environment.

00:12:07.430 --> 00:12:12.400
And there are others, and we want to hear
what those others are.

00:12:12.520 --> 00:12:14.920
We really want to get a
feeling for how it is that you

00:12:14.920 --> 00:12:16.560
people are using the product.

00:12:16.630 --> 00:12:19.520
Because the clearer the
feedback you give us,

00:12:19.520 --> 00:12:22.490
the better the product
we can deliver to you.

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:27.240
So what is it that we're
talking about here?

00:12:27.300 --> 00:12:29.040
Apple Managed Desktop.

00:12:29.170 --> 00:12:33.000
So Apple Managed Desktop is a
mechanism for managing resources.

00:12:33.380 --> 00:12:35.280
And what is that?

00:12:35.280 --> 00:12:37.110
Well, that's people.

00:12:37.250 --> 00:12:41.930
So I manage people by
managing user lists,

00:12:41.960 --> 00:12:45.640
by managing passwords
and password policies.

00:12:45.640 --> 00:12:49.200
It's managing equipment settings,
and there's some new

00:12:49.220 --> 00:12:51.080
ones that we're managing.

00:12:51.660 --> 00:12:54.500
It's, you know,
does the computer turn off

00:12:54.590 --> 00:12:56.680
at 10 o'clock at night?

00:12:57.090 --> 00:12:59.960
Do I have screensavers come on?

00:13:00.110 --> 00:13:05.510
Not screensavers,
but does the monitor dim automatically?

00:13:05.690 --> 00:13:07.710
Do you have access to these
kinds of applications?

00:13:07.720 --> 00:13:10.040
Applications are resources.

00:13:10.060 --> 00:13:11.060
So how do we do that?

00:13:11.060 --> 00:13:15.540
We do that through Workgroup Manager,
primarily.

00:13:15.540 --> 00:13:18.980
Capabilities is handled through the
system in a small kind of environment.

00:13:18.980 --> 00:13:21.610
But what you have is you have
your personal environment

00:13:21.610 --> 00:13:23.240
where you have your accounts.

00:13:23.240 --> 00:13:27.020
And if you move from accounts
on a local level for a system,

00:13:27.030 --> 00:13:29.320
you move to Workgroup Manager.

00:13:29.410 --> 00:13:33.320
Workgroup Manager basically is
a bigger accounts management

00:13:33.320 --> 00:13:35.480
thing with lots more options.

00:13:35.480 --> 00:13:39.020
Because you have lots
more that you can control.

00:13:39.020 --> 00:13:41.830
But what is Workgroup Manager?

00:13:41.840 --> 00:13:46.100
Workgroup Manager is
primarily a directory editor.

00:13:46.100 --> 00:13:49.380
It edits data that sits in a directory.

00:13:49.380 --> 00:13:55.080
And that's going to become much
clearer to you all with Panther.

00:13:55.080 --> 00:14:00.390
Because for me,
a key feature of Workgroup

00:14:00.390 --> 00:14:05.360
Manager in Panther is the inspector.

00:14:05.360 --> 00:14:12.730
Because that gives me the ability
to go in and edit my directory raw.

00:14:13.800 --> 00:14:17.050
That's a lot of power,
and there's not a lot of sanity

00:14:17.050 --> 00:14:19.080
checking that happens when that goes on.

00:14:19.080 --> 00:14:22.010
So, you know,
buyer beware--user beware in

00:14:22.080 --> 00:14:24.190
this particular situation.

00:14:24.780 --> 00:14:41.210
What we do in my group,
which primarily handles the

00:14:41.210 --> 00:14:41.210
preference setting--and as we
look into Workgroup Manager,

00:14:41.210 --> 00:14:41.210
you'll see, and we'll be dealing a lot
with the preference setting--is

00:14:41.210 --> 00:14:41.210
we take those preferences and
we put them into an XML file.

00:14:41.760 --> 00:14:45.950
into an XML format, and we store those in
the directory structure.

00:14:45.950 --> 00:14:50.310
We really don't,
and then when a user logs in,

00:14:50.530 --> 00:14:56.050
we go out to the server based on what
machine the user is logging in on,

00:14:56.050 --> 00:14:59.060
who the user is,
what groups they're part of

00:14:59.070 --> 00:15:02.870
or have chosen to be part of
for this particular session.

00:15:03.050 --> 00:15:05.970
And we get that XML data
out of the directory.

00:15:05.970 --> 00:15:09.850
We unionize it or munge it,
put it down to the local system,

00:15:09.850 --> 00:15:12.230
and that sets what their preferences are.

00:15:12.240 --> 00:15:22.140
We also do volume mounting as part of
the programmatic process that happens.

00:15:22.140 --> 00:15:25.190
We also pass information off
to the system so that if you

00:15:25.190 --> 00:15:28.200
have applications that need to
launch or those kinds of things,

00:15:28.210 --> 00:15:30.860
we set those preferences so
that other system services

00:15:30.860 --> 00:15:32.560
can take advantage of those.

00:15:32.560 --> 00:15:35.830
But we really don't do a lot
of actions other than that.

00:15:37.150 --> 00:15:40.700
We are not access control lists.

00:15:41.800 --> 00:15:46.590
Though we do allow for permissions
and preferences and things like that,

00:15:46.700 --> 00:15:49.950
we're not setting up
access control lists.

00:15:52.320 --> 00:15:56.140
So we have a managed environment.

00:15:56.140 --> 00:16:01.090
The top of the managed
environment chain for us is users.

00:16:01.460 --> 00:16:06.380
The first thing you do is you
set up users and you set them up

00:16:06.380 --> 00:16:09.000
usually with home directories.

00:16:09.000 --> 00:16:10.000
Not always.

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:13.090
Because I can set up a series of users
and they don't have home directories

00:16:13.090 --> 00:16:15.920
and maybe they're all FTP users.

00:16:17.160 --> 00:16:18.080
In that case, they're managed.

00:16:18.100 --> 00:16:19.250
They're managed FTP users.

00:16:19.260 --> 00:16:23.350
They don't have--they're not going to
be accessing this particular device,

00:16:23.410 --> 00:16:25.860
and so they don't have home directories.

00:16:27.460 --> 00:16:30.120
In those home directories,
we store preferences.

00:16:30.260 --> 00:16:33.720
So again,
a bunch has changed with Panther,

00:16:33.720 --> 00:16:37.080
and the things that you as
developers and you as IT folks

00:16:37.080 --> 00:16:44.310
really need to pay attention to,
and that is today with Jaguar,

00:16:44.370 --> 00:16:48.720
I sit down and I log in as me.

00:16:48.720 --> 00:16:51.760
And until I log out,
I'm the only one using the

00:16:51.760 --> 00:16:53.430
machine for the most part.

00:16:53.430 --> 00:16:56.920
Now, I know people can SSH in,
people can FTP in,

00:16:57.090 --> 00:17:00.130
people can do a bunch of stuff.

00:17:00.670 --> 00:17:07.190
But as far as accessing freestanding,
native Mac OS X, you know,

00:17:07.220 --> 00:17:12.450
GUI applications, I'm the only one that's
doing any of that.

00:17:12.600 --> 00:17:25.200
[Transcript missing]

00:17:26.310 --> 00:17:32.090
So that I can get up from my desk,
go to lunch, or I can be in a lab and be

00:17:32.090 --> 00:17:35.510
sitting there and accessing it,
and then my lab partner can

00:17:35.650 --> 00:17:37.540
switch over to their account.

00:17:37.550 --> 00:17:41.840
So now you have two people logged
into the machine at the same time.

00:17:42.020 --> 00:17:48.260
And application developer me puts
all those things in a global space,

00:17:48.460 --> 00:17:51.030
or with an absolute path,

00:17:51.240 --> 00:17:55.830
Well, User 2 can't access the data
that User 1 is accessing because

00:17:55.830 --> 00:17:57.600
I've got it open and running.

00:17:57.600 --> 00:18:01.570
So those are some of the things that
you really need to be thinking about

00:18:01.730 --> 00:18:06.200
when you're developing solutions or
when you're testing out your products.

00:18:07.120 --> 00:18:09.000
Don't require specific folders.

00:18:09.380 --> 00:18:13.000
Now, last year when I was giving
this kind of presentation,

00:18:13.000 --> 00:18:17.390
I had a whole scenario where I showed
a demo and I ran FS usage on a

00:18:17.390 --> 00:18:20.830
bunch of applications and showed
how some applications were being

00:18:20.830 --> 00:18:25.210
bad and they were doing lots of I/O,
and if you have I/O over the network,

00:18:25.210 --> 00:18:26.000
it's bad.

00:18:26.000 --> 00:18:28.990
I tried to look for some applications
that were doing some bad things.

00:18:29.000 --> 00:18:32.000
Early iterations of
some people's software,

00:18:32.070 --> 00:18:35.000
if you didn't have a specific
folder with a specific name,

00:18:35.000 --> 00:18:37.590
the application would crash.

00:18:37.900 --> 00:18:42.290
Now, if you want a specific folder,
some of these applications,

00:18:42.450 --> 00:18:48.600
they will create a new application
with that particular folder.

00:18:49.500 --> 00:18:53.050
Our customers like to customize.

00:18:53.100 --> 00:18:55.200
Customers customize.

00:18:55.260 --> 00:19:00.280
And don't require them to
have a specific folder.

00:19:00.310 --> 00:19:04.170
Don't, you know,
"My App Folder." So you provide

00:19:04.200 --> 00:19:09.940
an application and it has to have
these--don't use specific folder names.

00:19:09.940 --> 00:19:09.940
Use relative names where possible.

00:19:10.300 --> 00:19:20.020
Allow for one installation per CPU,
but don't require--don't disallow

00:19:20.400 --> 00:19:23.140
multiple users from accessing
that particular application.

00:19:23.190 --> 00:19:26.200
This is, you know,
the fast user switching scenario.

00:19:26.200 --> 00:19:29.570
You can't be sure that only
one person is going to be

00:19:29.570 --> 00:19:32.020
trying to run your application.

00:19:32.690 --> 00:19:34.400
You're going to be multiple
users in the machine.

00:19:34.540 --> 00:19:40.530
Also assume that your application
will be accessed over the network.

00:19:41.400 --> 00:19:42.440
So why is that?

00:19:42.470 --> 00:19:45.350
Well, that's for a couple of reasons.

00:19:45.630 --> 00:19:49.530
I do some beta testing for
some Mac OS X applications,

00:19:49.530 --> 00:19:51.900
which I can't talk about
because they're still in beta.

00:19:52.090 --> 00:19:57.450
And one of the first bugs I wrote
on these applications was I logged

00:19:57.450 --> 00:20:01.840
in using my network user ID,
which is out on the network,

00:20:01.840 --> 00:20:04.600
and I tried to run the application,
and it crashed.

00:20:04.610 --> 00:20:09.010
It didn't like me not running locally.

00:20:09.500 --> 00:20:11.310
It also didn't like me
not running as admin,

00:20:11.570 --> 00:20:15.240
which is a totally also
different scenario.

00:20:15.240 --> 00:20:17.010
So there are two different things.

00:20:17.020 --> 00:20:20.250
One, assume that if I'm doing I/O,
for example,

00:20:20.250 --> 00:20:25.040
if I'm writing out to a cache or I'm
storing files in temporary folders,

00:20:25.040 --> 00:20:27.630
if they're stored out on the network.

00:20:28.010 --> 00:20:31.180
You have to assume that where
that user's home directory is

00:20:31.420 --> 00:20:33.440
could be out on the network.

00:20:33.440 --> 00:20:36.740
And that if it's out over the network,
what we ran into here this morning

00:20:37.110 --> 00:20:41.030
is there's a really big airport
configuration here for all of

00:20:41.030 --> 00:20:43.150
you guys to have airport access.

00:20:43.590 --> 00:20:46.140
That can get really busy.

00:20:46.140 --> 00:20:49.670
And if I'm booting or running
multiple applications,

00:20:49.670 --> 00:20:52.600
all of them over airport,
and all of this data's in

00:20:52.600 --> 00:20:56.610
various network home directories,
it might not be the fastest

00:20:56.610 --> 00:20:58.500
airport implementation.

00:20:58.500 --> 00:21:00.430
In a lot of cases,
we have airport solutions

00:21:00.790 --> 00:21:04.350
that we've sold to schools,
and they haven't updated to the new,

00:21:04.410 --> 00:21:05.880
faster airports.

00:21:05.880 --> 00:21:10.680
So they're accessing their network
folders over airport with 30,

00:21:10.680 --> 00:21:15.540
40 people connecting to the same
airport base station at the same time,

00:21:15.540 --> 00:21:18.310
and the performance goes into the toilet.

00:21:18.320 --> 00:21:21.970
So you as developers need to take that
into consideration when you're building.

00:21:21.980 --> 00:21:27.730
You're writing your applications.

00:21:28.370 --> 00:21:33.070
Don't require the users to run your
applications if you're developers

00:21:33.070 --> 00:21:35.910
out there to have admin access.

00:21:36.200 --> 00:21:39.560
As we get back to the usage scenario,
most of our users aren't

00:21:39.620 --> 00:21:40.970
running as admins.

00:21:41.070 --> 00:21:43.100
Most of them are running
as network users,

00:21:43.100 --> 00:21:51.070
and some percentage of them know an
admin password for their machine,

00:21:51.070 --> 00:21:51.070
but

00:21:51.220 --> 00:21:58.060
A large number of customers do not,
and some subset of

00:21:58.060 --> 00:22:03.400
customers--one customer,
two customers--might be 40,000 users,

00:22:03.560 --> 00:22:06.540
where none of those 40,000
users know their admin password.

00:22:06.590 --> 00:22:11.450
So, use our product to test your product.

