00:22:21.090 --> 00:22:22.500
Workgroup Manager.

00:22:22.500 --> 00:22:23.280
What is Workgroup Manager?

00:22:23.280 --> 00:22:27.390
Workgroup Manager is a way to
manage system-level preferences.

00:22:28.810 --> 00:22:35.290
How many of you have used
Workgroup Manager here on Jaguar?

00:22:36.610 --> 00:22:41.480
So about 20-25%. For those
of you who have not,

00:22:41.530 --> 00:22:43.460
Workgroup Manager allows
you to set preferences into

00:22:43.460 --> 00:22:45.940
three separate categories.

00:22:45.940 --> 00:22:47.980
I'll be showing you a Workgroup
Manager demo here in a bit,

00:22:47.980 --> 00:22:53.120
and I'll go into a little bit more
because 75% of you haven't used it.

00:22:53.120 --> 00:22:56.440
Basically we have the notion
of three different groupings.

00:22:56.440 --> 00:22:58.640
We have users,
which I think you're all familiar with.

00:22:58.640 --> 00:23:02.380
We have groups,
which you're sort of all familiar with.

00:23:02.380 --> 00:23:05.260
The users are part of groups,
and you're familiar with that.

00:23:05.260 --> 00:23:08.580
And then we have computer lists.

00:23:08.580 --> 00:23:14.810
So basically what happens is
when the machine boots up,

00:23:14.810 --> 00:23:19.990
it is bound to--in most cases or
in a lot of cases--it's bound to

00:23:19.990 --> 00:23:21.840
some directory in the network.

00:23:21.840 --> 00:23:24.280
So it gets network
services available to it.

00:23:24.280 --> 00:23:26.380
It's bound to some directory.

00:23:26.380 --> 00:23:30.890
And the machine will go to that
directory and find out whether or not

00:23:30.890 --> 00:23:34.020
it knows about me on the computer.

00:23:34.020 --> 00:23:35.020
Does it know about me?

00:23:35.020 --> 00:23:37.780
In its list, yes or no.

00:23:37.810 --> 00:23:42.110
If I am, are there any preferences
associated with me,

00:23:42.110 --> 00:23:43.960
my specific device?

00:23:43.960 --> 00:23:45.870
There may or may not be.

00:23:46.470 --> 00:23:54.560
If I'm not in a list of known computers,
does the binding handle guest computers?

00:23:54.560 --> 00:23:57.600
So anybody who comes and
plugs in their machine.

00:23:57.600 --> 00:23:59.880
And what preferences are
associated with that?

00:23:59.880 --> 00:24:03.610
Maybe I require everybody who logs
into my network to have a list log in.

00:24:03.630 --> 00:24:05.920
things like that,
we'll show you some of that when we get

00:24:05.920 --> 00:24:08.420
into showing your workgroup manager.

00:24:08.420 --> 00:24:11.320
Then, it puts up the user list.

00:24:11.320 --> 00:24:13.070
You get a user list,
I get to pick what user

00:24:13.200 --> 00:24:14.560
I want to log in as.

00:24:14.560 --> 00:24:20.020
Once I've logged in as that user,
then I get to pick what group the user

00:24:20.020 --> 00:24:22.570
might be a member of multiple groups.

00:24:22.570 --> 00:24:25.900
And I can set preferences
at each of those levels,

00:24:25.900 --> 00:24:29.500
and we'll show you how we do that.

00:24:29.570 --> 00:24:32.900
Workgroup manager also sets non-MCX data.

00:24:32.900 --> 00:24:35.950
That's the MCX data,
for system level preferences,

00:24:35.950 --> 00:24:36.920
as we'll see.

00:24:36.920 --> 00:24:41.020
It also sets up non-MCX data.

00:24:41.020 --> 00:24:43.900
This is workgroup manager,
where I go and I add users.

00:24:43.900 --> 00:24:46.960
And I add home directories.

00:24:46.990 --> 00:24:50.570
I add group volumes that
are accessible to them.

00:24:51.630 --> 00:24:57.010
and I set up parameters and
policies for those users.

00:24:57.280 --> 00:25:02.570
This user has a home .
They have 5K of storage in it,

00:25:02.600 --> 00:25:05.400
because I don't have--I have
thousands and thousands of users

00:25:05.400 --> 00:25:09.370
using this particular machine,
and I don't want them to have

00:25:09.370 --> 00:25:10.890
a lot of network storage.

00:25:10.990 --> 00:25:13.710
5K is really small,
but let's say 5 meg or 100 meg

00:25:13.710 --> 00:25:15.500
or something--something small.

00:25:15.570 --> 00:25:19.880
So--but I'm already managing
those users by telling them,

00:25:19.880 --> 00:25:25.070
"This is how much storage you have
on my network devices." The other

00:25:25.070 --> 00:25:29.480
thing to remember with Workgroup
Manager is it's directory-centric.

00:25:29.490 --> 00:25:32.490
So I can set this thing
up in a directory,

00:25:32.490 --> 00:25:36.140
I can configure users,
and those users could have

00:25:36.260 --> 00:25:40.390
home directories on a totally
different set of machines.

00:25:41.750 --> 00:25:44.760
Setup in Workgroup Manager:
Where those home directories are

00:25:44.960 --> 00:25:49.700
does not need to be on the machine
that is holding the information.

00:25:49.700 --> 00:25:51.690
So,
Workgroup Manager is a directory-centric,

00:25:51.690 --> 00:25:54.690
it's not a server-centric configuration.

00:25:54.700 --> 00:25:57.830
Again, take the Wayback
Machine back five years ago,

00:25:57.830 --> 00:26:01.800
and what we were dealing with was
Apple Share and Apple Share IP,

00:26:01.950 --> 00:26:06.270
where your user list was
specific to a specific machine.

00:26:06.540 --> 00:26:10.490
What we do when we move into
a directory-centric model is,

00:26:10.560 --> 00:26:15.180
"I can have the same username and
password and have that be accessible

00:26:15.190 --> 00:26:18.040
in multiple different arenas."

